-- ── Braintrust ──────────────────────────────────────────────
UPDATE tools SET
  short_description = COALESCE($q$There are two unrelated companies named Braintrust. This profile covers Braintrust (braintrust.dev), an AI observability and evaluation platform founded in 2023 by Ankur Goyal, previously founder of Impira (acquired by Figma), and headquartered in San Francisco. Braintrust helps teams building LLM-powered products and AI agents trace requests in production, run offline evaluations against datasets, score outputs with LLM graders, code, or human review, and catch quality regressions before they reach users. Its eval-first philosophy starts from defining what a good output looks like and measuring against that, rather than only capturing logs and searching after the fact. The platform includes Loop, an AI assistant that analyzes production traces and recommends custom scorers, and Brainstore, a purpose-built data store for querying millions of nested agent traces quickly. In February 2026 the company raised an 80 million dollar Series B led by ICONIQ at an 800 million dollar valuation. Note: this is a different company from Braintrust (usebraintrust.com), a blockchain-based, token-incentivized freelance talent marketplace founded in San Jose in 2018 by Adam Jackson, Gabriel Luna-Ostaseski, and Brian Flynn - do not confuse the two.$q$, short_description),
  pricing_model = COALESCE($q$Freemium, usage-based pricing (data processed, scores, and retention)$q$, pricing_model),
  starting_price = COALESCE($q$Free Starter plan; Pro plan from $249 per month$q$, starting_price),
  founded_year = COALESCE(2023, founded_year),
  company_size = COALESCE($q$Growth-stage startup; exact headcount not independently confirmed, well-funded following an $80M Series B in February 2026$q$, company_size),
  headquarters = COALESCE($q$San Francisco, California, USA$q$, headquarters),
  languages = ARRAY[$q$English$q$]::text[],
  seo_title = COALESCE($q$Braintrust Review: AI Evaluation and LLM Observability Platform$q$, seo_title),
  seo_meta_description = COALESCE($q$Braintrust (braintrust.dev) is an eval-first AI observability platform for tracing, testing and improving LLM apps. See pricing, features, and how it differs from usebraintrust.com.$q$, seo_meta_description),
  llm_readable_summary = COALESCE($q$Because the name 'Braintrust' is shared by two unrelated companies, it's worth being precise about which one this profile describes. Braintrust (braintrust.dev) is an AI observability and evaluation platform founded in 2023 by Ankur Goyal, who previously founded Impira, a data-extraction and document-management company that was acquired by Figma, where Goyal went on to lead the AI team before starting Braintrust. Headquartered in San Francisco, Braintrust exists to solve a problem that became urgent as teams shipped more LLM-powered products and AI agents into production: traditional software observability tools weren't built for the non-deterministic, quality-sensitive nature of AI outputs, and traditional testing frameworks weren't built for probabilistic model behavior. Braintrust's approach is described as 'eval-first' - rather than starting from 'capture everything and search later,' the platform encourages teams to define what a good output looks like first, build a dataset and scoring criteria around that definition, and then continuously measure new prompts, models, and code changes against it. In practice this plays out across a few connected capabilities. Tracing lets teams inspect every request, tool call, and step of an AI agent's reasoning in production, searching across millions of logs and tracking latency, cost, and quality in real time. The evaluation framework lets teams run experiments against real datasets, compare prompts and models side by side, and score outputs using LLM-based graders, code-based scorers, or human reviewers, which is particularly useful for catching regressions before a prompt or model change reaches end users. Two more specialized capabilities round out the platform: Loop, an AI assistant for evaluation development that can take a natural-language description of a failure a team wants to investigate and use it to analyze production traces, generate a relevant evaluation dataset, and recommend custom scorers; and Brainstore, a data store purpose-built for AI workloads, designed to support fast queries across millions of agent traces, including large nested trace trees and high-cardinality observability data that general-purpose logging systems struggle with. Braintrust is explicitly framework- and model-agnostic, offering SDKs for Python, TypeScript, Go, Ruby, and C#, and it's designed to slot into an existing AI stack without requiring a rewrite. Its customer base includes well-known technology companies such as Notion, Stripe, Vercel, Airtable, Instacart, Zapier, Ramp, Dropbox, Cloudflare, and BILL, with Notion publicly crediting the platform for a significant improvement in how quickly it can find and fix AI quality issues. The company's momentum has been reflected in its funding: in February 2026, Braintrust raised an 80 million dollar Series B led by ICONIQ, with participation from Andreessen Horowitz, Greylock, and Elad Gil, at an 800 million dollar valuation. It's worth being clear about the other 'Braintrust': usebraintrust.com is a completely different, unrelated company - a blockchain-based, token-incentivized freelance talent marketplace founded in San Jose in 2018 by Adam Jackson, Gabriel Luna-Ostaseski, and Brian Flynn, which connects vetted knowledge workers with enterprise clients like Nestle, Porsche, and Nike, charges a flat percent project fee, and uses its BTRST token to distribute governance and rewards across the network. Anyone researching 'Braintrust' for hiring/marketplace purposes should look at usebraintrust.com, while anyone researching 'Braintrust' for AI evaluation, observability, or LLM tooling purposes should look at braintrust.dev, which is the company profiled here.$q$, llm_readable_summary),
  status = 'published',
  noindex = false,
  sitemap_eligible = true,
  published_at = COALESCE(published_at, now()),
  updated_at = now()
WHERE id = '4780ba32-7996-4e79-bff8-bb8b30ce99d3';

